    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is expected value thinking?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Expected value thinking is a decision framework that multiplies the probability of each possible outcome by its value, then sums the results. Instead of asking 'what will happen?' it asks 'what is the average outcome across all the ways this could play out?' This reframes decisions from single predictions to probability-weighted evaluations of all possible futures."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do I need to do math to use expected value thinking?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. While expected value has a precise mathematical definition, the real value of EV thinking is the habit of mind it creates — explicitly considering multiple outcomes, estimating their likelihood, and weighting them before deciding. Rough estimates and directional reasoning are far more useful than no EV thinking at all."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do good expected value decisions sometimes produce bad outcomes?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Because expected value is about average outcomes across many instances, not guaranteed outcomes in a single instance. A 70% chance of success still fails 30% of the time. The correct response to a bad outcome from a good EV decision is to examine the process, not reverse the decision. Judging decisions by outcomes rather than the quality of reasoning at decision time is called resulting — a common and costly error."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the biggest mistake people make with expected value?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The most common mistake is ignoring tail risks — low-probability, catastrophic outcomes that can be fatal even if the expected value calculation looks positive. A decision with positive EV but a 5% chance of total ruin may not be worth taking, depending on the stakes. Kelly Criterion and other risk-adjustment tools help account for this."
        }
      }
    ]
