  <article itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <div class="article-meta">
        <span class="category-badge">Decision Making</span>
        <span class="read-time">{readingTime} min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 itemprop="headline">{pageTitle}</h1>
      <p class="article-subtitle">Most decisions are made as if the future is certain. It isn't. Expected value thinking gives you a rigorous framework for reasoning when outcomes are uncertain — the way professional investors, poker players, and elite decision-makers actually think.</p>
      <div class="author-info">
        <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
          <span itemprop="name">{author}</span>
        </span>
        <time itemprop="datePublished" datetime={datePublished}>May 9, 2026</time>
      </div>
    </header>

    <figure class="article-hero">
      <Image
        src={heroImage}
        alt="Expected Value Thinking: Make Better Decisions Under Uncertainty"
        width={1200}
        height={630}
        fetchpriority="high"
        loading="eager"
      />
    </figure>

    <div class="article-body" itemprop="articleBody">

      <section>
        <h2>The Problem with How Most People Decide</h2>
        <p>Ask most people how they make decisions and they'll describe some version of predicting the future: they think about what they expect to happen, weigh the pros and cons, and choose based on the most likely scenario. This feels rational. It isn't.</p>
        <p>The problem is that "the most likely scenario" is rarely the only scenario, and often isn't even the most important one. A business venture with a 60% chance of modest success and a 40% chance of transformative success is a very different decision than one with a 60% chance of modest success and a 40% chance of catastrophic failure — even though the most likely scenario is identical in both cases.</p>
        <p>What's missing is a way of thinking that accounts for all the ways things could go — weighted by how likely each is. That framework is expected value.</p>

        <ContentBox type="highlight" title="The Core Formula">
          Expected Value = Σ (Probability of Outcome × Value of Outcome)<br/><br/>
          In plain terms: for each possible result, multiply how likely it is by how much it's worth. Add them all up. The sum is the expected value — the average outcome if you could play the decision out many times.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>A Simple Example That Changes How You Think</h2>
        <p>You're offered a coin flip. Heads: you win $150. Tails: you lose $100. Should you take it?</p>
        <p>Most people's gut says no — losing $100 feels worse than winning $150 feels good. This is loss aversion at work, and it's wrong here.</p>
        <p>The expected value calculation: (0.5 × $150) + (0.5 × −$100) = $75 − $50 = <strong>+$25</strong>.</p>
        <p>On average, you gain $25 per flip. If you played this game 100 times, you'd expect to walk away with approximately $2,500. Declining this offer — which most people do — is irrational. You're letting a feeling override a calculation that clearly favors acceptance.</p>
        <p>Now flip it: heads you win $120, tails you lose $100. EV = (0.5 × $120) + (0.5 × −$100) = $60 − $50 = <strong>+$10</strong>. Still positive — still worth accepting if you can play repeatedly without the $100 loss being ruinous.</p>
        <p>The insight isn't the arithmetic. It's what the arithmetic forces: you have to think about all possible outcomes, not just the one you hope for or fear most.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Expected Value Beyond the Math</h2>
        <p>Most real decisions don't have clean probabilities or dollar values. You can't run the formula precisely for career moves, relationship decisions, or business strategies. That's fine — the value of EV thinking isn't the calculation. It's the habit of mind.</p>
        <p>What EV thinking actually changes is how you approach any decision under uncertainty:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>You stop asking "what will happen?" and start asking "what are all the ways this could play out?"</strong></li>
          <li>You explicitly estimate probabilities instead of thinking in terms of what you expect or hope.</li>
          <li>You weight outcomes by both their likelihood and their magnitude — a small chance of a huge outcome matters; a large chance of a trivial outcome may not.</li>
          <li>You separate the quality of a decision from its outcome — good decisions can produce bad results, and bad decisions can get lucky.</li>
        </ul>

        <ContentBox type="info" title="Annie Duke on Resulting">
          Professional poker player and decision scientist Annie Duke coined the term "resulting" — the tendency to evaluate the quality of a decision by its outcome. A bad player who wins a hand tends to think they played well. A good player who loses on a 70/30 favorite tends to think something went wrong. Both are mistakes. The quality of a decision is determined by the reasoning at the time it was made, not by what happened afterward.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

      <!-- Fluid In-Article Ad -->
      <ins class="adsbygoogle"
        style="display:block; text-align:center;"
        data-ad-layout="in-article"
        data-ad-format="fluid"
