      <section>
        <h2>EV Thinking in Real Decisions</h2>
        <p>Abstract examples make EV thinking feel like a finance exercise. Here's how it actually applies to decisions that matter.</p>

        <h3>Career Decisions</h3>
        <p>You're considering leaving a stable job to join an early-stage startup. The "most likely scenario" thinking goes: probably won't work, I'll lose income, risky. Stop there and you decline.</p>
        <p>EV thinking goes further. Map the outcomes: 70% chance the startup struggles and you need to find a new job in 18 months (cost: disruption, 3-6 months to re-stabilize). 20% chance of moderate success, startup grows, you gain valuable equity and experience (value: significant). 10% chance of breakout success (value: potentially life-changing). Weight each by its value. Now the expected value may look very different — especially if the downside is survivable and the upside is large.</p>
        <p>This isn't a calculation that gives you a number. It's a framework that stops you from letting the 70% case dominate a decision where the 10% case has 50× the magnitude.</p>

        <h3>Investment Decisions</h3>
        <p>EV thinking is the foundation of professional investing. A stock isn't worth buying because the most likely scenario is positive — it's worth buying if the probability-weighted value across all scenarios exceeds the price. This is why skilled investors often hold positions that look wrong most of the time but right enough of the time (and by enough magnitude) to produce positive expected returns.</p>
        <p>It's also why diversification makes EV sense: across many positions, the average return approaches the expected value. A single bet, even with high EV, carries variance that can wipe out a portfolio before the law of large numbers can work.</p>

        <h3>Business Strategy</h3>
        <p>Should you launch a new product line? Enter a new market? Hire aggressively? Each has a range of outcomes. EV thinking forces you to map the distribution: not just "what's the plan?" but "what happens if the plan works 50%? 30%? 10%? What's the downside look like at each level?" A strategy with a mediocre best case and catastrophic worst case is inferior to one with a great best case and manageable worst case — even if the "expected" outcome looks similar.</p>

        <ContentGrid columns={2} gap="md">
          <ContentBox type="tip" title="High EV Patterns">
            — Large upside, capped downside<br/>
            — Asymmetric bets where losses are bounded<br/>
            — Reversible decisions with fast feedback<br/>
            — Small experiments before large commitments<br/>
            — Options that preserve future flexibility
          </ContentBox>
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Low EV Patterns">
            — Small upside, catastrophic downside risk<br/>
            — Irreversible commitments with uncertain returns<br/>
            — Decisions driven by the most likely case alone<br/>
            — Ignoring tail scenarios because they feel unlikely<br/>
            — Optimizing for probability of success over magnitude
          </ContentBox>
        </ContentGrid>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The Asymmetry Principle</h2>
        <p>One of the most valuable insights that EV thinking produces is the principle of asymmetry: you don't need high probability to have high expected value. You need the right relationship between probability and magnitude.</p>
        <p>A 10% chance of a $1,000,000 gain has an expected value of $100,000. A 90% chance of a $50,000 gain has an expected value of $45,000. The first option is less likely to succeed — and nearly twice as valuable in expected terms.</p>
        <p>This is why venture capitalists make dozens of small bets rather than one large one: a portfolio of asymmetric bets — most of which fail, a few of which produce enormous returns — can have dramatically positive expected value even with a terrible win rate.</p>
        <p>The same logic applies to personal decisions. Many of the highest-EV moves in life have low probability of working out — starting a business, writing a book, pursuing an unconventional path — but the magnitude of the upside, combined with a survivable downside, produces positive expected value that conventional probability-focused thinking systematically misses.</p>

        <ContentBox type="highlight" title="The Barbell Strategy">
          Nassim Taleb popularized the barbell strategy: combine very safe positions with small, high-upside bets. Most of your resources go to low-risk, reliable outcomes. A small portion goes to high-variance, potentially transformative bets. The expected value of the portfolio is higher than either extreme alone — and you avoid the dangerous middle ground of medium-risk, medium-reward decisions that have neither safety nor meaningful upside.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The Critical Caveat: Ruin and the Kelly Criterion</h2>
        <p>Expected value thinking has one critical blind spot if applied naively: it doesn't account for ruin. A decision with positive expected value can still be catastrophic if the downside scenario eliminates your ability to play future rounds.</p>
        <p>The coin flip example assumed you could play 100 times. If you can only play once and losing $100 would mean you can't eat this week, the positive EV is irrelevant. The tail scenario — the bad outcome — is fatal, and fatal outcomes don't respond to averaging.</p>
        <p>This is why professional gamblers and investors use risk-adjusted frameworks. The most famous is the Kelly Criterion: bet a fraction of your capital proportional to your edge. Never bet in a way that risks ruin, even if the EV is highly positive. Survival comes first — because you need to be in the game to capture future EV opportunities.</p>

        <ContentBox type="warning" title="When to Override EV">
          Positive expected value does not automatically mean you should take a bet. Ask:<br/><br/>
          — Does the downside scenario threaten survival (financial, physical, reputational)?<br/>
          — Is this a one-time decision or one I can repeat many times?<br/>
          — Do I have sufficient resources to absorb the downside without being knocked out of the game?<br/><br/>
          If the answer to any of these makes the downside catastrophic, reduce the bet size or pass — even with positive EV.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>How to Estimate Probabilities Without Data</h2>
        <p>The most common objection to EV thinking is: "I don't know the probabilities." This is true — and irrelevant. You always have some information, and rough estimates based on that information are far better than ignoring probabilities entirely.</p>
        <p>Several techniques help calibrate estimates when hard data isn't available:</p>

        <h3>Reference Class Forecasting</h3>
        <p>Instead of asking "what do I think will happen in this specific case?" ask "what happens in cases like this one?" If you're considering launching a new product, look at the base rate of similar product launches. If you're evaluating a hiring decision, look at the base rate of success for hires made under similar conditions. External reference classes almost always produce better estimates than inside-view speculation.</p>

        <h3>Fermi Estimation</h3>
        <p>Break unknown quantities into components you can estimate separately, then combine. Instead of guessing "what's the probability this business succeeds?" ask: what fraction of businesses in this space survive 3 years? What fraction that survive 3 years reach the scale we're targeting? What differentiates us from the average? Each component estimate is easier than the whole — and combining them gives a reasonable approximation.</p>

        <h3>Pre-Mortem Calibration</h3>
        <p>Imagine you've made the decision and one year later, it has failed. What went wrong? This <a href="/blog/pre-mortem-technique">pre-mortem technique</a> surfaces the most plausible failure modes and gives you information about which scenarios deserve higher probability weight. (See our full guide on the pre-mortem technique.)</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Applying EV Thinking: A Practical Protocol</h2>

        <StepsList title="The EV Decision Framework">
          <li><strong>Map the outcome space.</strong> List 3-5 realistic scenarios: best case, worst case, most likely, and at least one tail scenario (very good or very bad outcome you haven't fully considered). Resist collapsing to a single prediction.</li>
          <li><strong>Estimate probabilities.</strong> Assign rough probability weights to each scenario. They don't need to be precise — directional accuracy matters more than false precision. Use reference class data where available. Ensure probabilities sum to 100%.</li>
          <li><strong>Estimate values.</strong> For each scenario, estimate the value or cost. This can be financial, but also include time cost, opportunity cost, stress, learning, and optionality created or destroyed. Try to make these at least roughly comparable across scenarios.</li>
          <li><strong>Calculate rough expected value.</strong> Multiply probability × value for each scenario and sum. Don't obsess over the number — the process of going through the calculation is what forces clear thinking.</li>
          <li><strong>Check for ruin scenarios.</strong> Identify any scenario that would threaten your ability to continue operating. If such a scenario exists with non-trivial probability (even 5-10%), adjust the bet size or add safeguards — regardless of the overall EV.</li>
          <li><strong>Compare to alternatives.</strong> EV thinking isn't just about whether a decision has positive expected value — it's about whether it has higher expected value than the alternatives, including doing nothing. Calculate EV for your main alternatives to put the decision in context.</li>
          <li><strong>Decide and record your reasoning.</strong> Make the decision based on EV analysis, and record your reasoning in a <a href="/blog/decision-journal">decision journal</a>. When you review outcomes later, you can assess whether your probability estimates were calibrated — the most valuable feedback loop for improving future EV thinking.</li>
        </StepsList>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>EV Thinking and the Long Game</h2>
        <p>The full power of expected value thinking only becomes apparent over time. In any single decision, a high-EV choice can produce a bad outcome. Over dozens or hundreds of decisions, the law of large numbers brings actual results close to expected values — and the person who consistently makes high-EV decisions will dramatically outperform the person who relies on intuition, fear, or the most likely scenario alone.</p>
        <p>This is how professional poker players, traders, and investors think about their craft. No single hand, trade, or investment proves or disproves their process. The question is always: am I making decisions with positive expected value? If yes, the outcomes will take care of themselves over time. If not, even a streak of lucky results doesn't validate the approach.</p>
        <p>The implication for anyone who wants to make systematically better decisions: build a track record of EV thinking, not a track record of good outcomes. Review your decisions against what you expected when you made them. Improve your probability estimates. Sharpen your ability to map outcome spaces. Over a decade of this practice, the results compound in ways that feel extraordinary — because most people never build this foundation.</p>

        <ContentBox type="tip" title="Key Takeaways">
          — Expected value = probability × magnitude, summed across all scenarios<br/>
          — The math matters less than the habit: always map multiple outcomes before deciding<br/>
          — Asymmetry is the key insight: low probability + high magnitude can dominate high probability + low magnitude<br/>
          — Never take positive EV bets that risk ruin — survival comes first<br/>
          — Calibrate probability estimates using reference classes, not just intuition<br/>
          — Judge decisions by the quality of reasoning at decision time, not by outcomes (avoid resulting)<br/>
          — EV thinking compounds: the benefit builds over hundreds of decisions, not one
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

